The recovery widens the success type to `Coords | null`; the error channel is narrowed because `AddressInvalid` has been handled.

```ts
import { Effect, Data } from "effect";

class Primary extends Data.TaggedError("Primary")<{}> {}
class Secondary extends Data.TaggedError("Secondary")<{}> {}

declare const main: Effect.Effect<number, Primary | Secondary>;
declare const backup: Effect.Effect<number, Secondary>;

export const orElse: Effect.Effect<number, Secondary> = main.pipe(
  Effect.catchTag("Primary", () => backup)
);
```

`Effect.catchTag` is the typed analogue of `TE.orElse` filtered to one error tag; the resulting error channel is the union of the remaining tags and the fallback's errors.

```ts
import { Effect, Data } from "effect";

interface Signup { readonly userId: string; readonly accepted: boolean }

class EmailInUse extends Data.TaggedError("EmailInUse")<{ readonly email: string }> {}
class WeakPassword extends Data.TaggedError("WeakPassword")<{ readonly score: number }> {}
class DbError extends Data.TaggedError("DbError")<{ readonly cause: unknown }> {}

declare const register: (
  email: string,
  pw: string
) => Effect.Effect<Signup, EmailInUse | WeakPassword | DbError>;

export const signup = (
  email: string,
  pw: string
): Effect.Effect<Signup, DbError> =>
  register(email, pw).pipe(
    Effect.catchTags({
      EmailInUse: () => Effect.succeed<Signup>({ userId: "", accepted: false }),
      WeakPassword: () => Effect.succeed<Signup>({ userId: "", accepted: false }),
    })
  );
```

Both validation tags are collapsed via `catchTags`; the only remaining error is `DbError`, cleanly visible in the public signature.

Each `Effect.catchTag("Name", handler)` returns a new effect where only the `Name` branch has been subtracted from the error union; stacking three of them peels errors off one at a time until the channel narrows to whatever is left (often `never`).

```ts
import { Effect, Data } from "effect";

class A extends Data.TaggedError("A")<{}> {}
class B extends Data.TaggedError("B")<{}> {}
class C extends Data.TaggedError("C")<{}> {}

declare const program: Effect.Effect<string, A | B | C>;

export const handled: Effect.Effect<string, C> = program.pipe(
  Effect.catchTag("A", () => Effect.succeed("a-recovered")),
  Effect.catchTag("B", () => Effect.succeed("b-recovered"))
);
```

After catching `A` then `B`, only `C` remains in `E`.

```ts
import { Effect, Data } from "effect";

class Recoverable extends Data.TaggedError("Recoverable")<{ readonly hint: string }> {}
class Fatal extends Data.TaggedError("Fatal")<{ readonly reason: string }> {}

declare const program: Effect.Effect<string, Recoverable | Fatal>;

export const safe: Effect.Effect<string, Fatal> = program.pipe(
  Effect.catchTag("Recoverable", (e) => Effect.succeed(e.hint))
);

export const safest: Effect.Effect<string, never> = safe.pipe(
  Effect.catchAll(() => Effect.succeed("catastrophe"))
);
```

The middle `safe` shows what `catchTag` leaves typed (`Fatal`); the final `catchAll` collapses everything, but `safe` is the interesting intermediate — callers can still handle `Fatal` specifically if they prefer.

```ts
import { Effect } from "effect";

class BadPayload { readonly _tag = "BadPayload" as const; constructor(readonly body: string) {} }
class EndpointDown { readonly _tag = "EndpointDown" as const; constructor(readonly url: string) {} }

declare const deliver: (
  url: string,
  body: string
) => Effect.Effect<void, BadPayload | EndpointDown>;

export const deliverOrDrop = (
  url: string,
  body: string
): Effect.Effect<void, EndpointDown> =>
  deliver(url, body).pipe(
    Effect.catchTag("BadPayload", () => Effect.void)
  );
```

Client mistakes are dropped silently via `catchTag`; server-side outages stay in the `E` channel where a supervising retry policy can inspect `_tag` and decide to back off.
